{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Salita del Petraio, Pensione Haase]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio comprises a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Salita del Petraio, Pensione Haase]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] neighborhood of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio are a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAccess", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Vasily Stalin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{ref improve|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Vasily Stalin\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image         = \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d, 1942 \u0433\u043e\u0434.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Vasily in 1942\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| birth_name    = Vasily Iosifovich Dzhugashvili \n| other_name    =\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1921|3|21}}\n| birth_place   = Moscow, [[Russian SFSR]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1962|3|19|1921|3|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Kazan]], Russian SFSR, Soviet Union\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Soviet Union|1936}} \n| branch        = [[Soviet Air Forces]]\n| serviceyears  = 1938\u20131953\n| serviceyears_label =\n| rank          = [[File:CCCP army Rank general-lejtnant infobox.svg|30px]] [[Lieutenant general]]\n| rank_label    =\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[1st Baltic Front]]<br>[[1st Belorussian Front]]\n| commands      = \n| battles_label = \n| battles       = [[World War II]] \n*[[Battle of Berlin]]\n| awards        = [[Order of the Red Banner]]\n| spouse        = {{ubl|Galina Burdonskaia|Yekaterina Semyonovna Timoshenko|Kapitolina Georgievna Vasil'yeva|Maria Ignat'yeva Nusberg}}\n| relations     = {{ubl|[[Joseph Stalin]] (father)|[[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]] (mother)|[[Svetlana Alliluyeva]] (sister)|[[Yakov Dzhugashvili]] (half-brother)|[[Konstantin Kuzakov]] (half-brother)}}\n| children      = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n\n'''Vasily Iosifovich Stalin''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0301\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0418\u043e\u0301\u0441\u0438\u0444\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0438\u043d}}; n\u00e9 '''Dzhugashvili'''; {{lang-ru|link=no|\u0414\u0436\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0448\u0432\u0438\u0301\u043b\u0438}}; 21 March 1921 \u2013 19 March 1962) was the son of [[Joseph Stalin]] by his second wife, [[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]].\n\n==Early life==\nStalin was born on 21 March 1921, the son of [[Joseph Stalin]] and [[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]]. He had an older half-brother, [[Yakov Dzhugashvili]] (born 1907), from his father's first marriage to [[Kato Svanidze]], and a younger sister, [[Svetlana Alliluyeva|Svetlana]], was born in 1926.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=15}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Kotkin|2014|p=466}}</ref> The family also took in [[Artyom Sergeyev]], the son of [[Fyodor Sergeyev]], a close friend of Joseph. Fyodor died four months after the birth of Artyom in an accident, so the boy was raised in the Stalin household.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=351}}</ref>\n\nAs his mother was interested in pursuing a professional career, a [[nanny]], Alexandra Bychokova, was hired to look after Stalin and Svetlana.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|pp=23\u201324}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 1932 his mother shot herself.<ref>{{harvnb|Kotkin|2017|pp=110\u2013111}}</ref> To conceal the suicide, the children were told that Alliluyeva had died of [[peritonitis]], a complication from [[appendicitis]]. It would be 10 years before they learned the truth of their mother's death.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=53}}</ref> Svetlana would later write that the death of their mother had a profound impact on her brother. She noted that he started to [[alcoholism|drink alcohol]] at the age of 13, and in drunken episodes would curse and attack her.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=72}}</ref> \n\nStarting from the death of Alliluyeva, Joseph Stalin ceased to visit his children; only the nursemaid and head of Stalin's security guards looked after Vasily and his sister. One officer, Sergei Efimov, was charged with continuously looking after the two children.\n\n==Military service==\nVasily started his active military service in the 16th Fighter Aviation Regiment in Moscow.{{when|date=January 2019}} Here he met Galina Burdonskaia, his future wife. They married when Vasily was 19.\n\nHe was transferred to the front in August 1941, and given the surname Ivanov in an attempt to conceal his identity. As the son of Stalin he flew in combat rarely, and when he did he was accompanied by a [[Formation flying|formation]]. In total Stalin took part in 29 combat missions, and is said to have shot down two enemy aircraft.<ref name=\"Kun 360\">{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=360}}</ref> As the son of the Soviet leader, Stalin was hated by most of his colleagues, who felt he was an informant to his father.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=357}}</ref> In the spring of 1942 he was sent back to Moscow, and given a role inspecting the conditions of the air force, and mainly stayed in Moscow for the rest of the war.<ref name=\"Kun 360\"/> Bored in this role, Stalin found himself in trouble after an 4 April 1943 incident where he had explosives dropped into the [[Moskva River]], injuring himself and killing the flight engineer.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=361}}</ref> \n\nAs a result of the explosion, Stalin was demoted, though within a year and a half he was promoted to command an air division. He was further promoted to general, and at the age of 24 was made the youngest [[major-general]] in the [[Red Army]]. He was also awarded several decorations, including the [[Order of Red Banner]] (twice), the [[Order of Alexander Nevsky]], and the [[Order of Suvarov]]. After the war he was transferred to Germany as part of the [[Soviet occupation zone|Soviet occupation]].<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=362}}</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to major-general in 1946, to Lieutenant-General in 1947, and to Commander of the [[Air Forces of the Moscow Military District]] in 1948.\n\n==Arrest and imprisonment==\nJoseph Stalin died on 4 March 1953. Vasily arrived shortly after the death of his father, and in a drunken rage claimed his father had been poisoned.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=184}}</ref> After his father's death, a long period of troubles began for Stalin. The [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Defense Ministry]] offered him to take up command of any [[Military districts of the Soviet Union|military district]], but he would only accept Moscow. This was not possible so instead Stalin was forced to retire from the military.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=224}}</ref> Less than two months after his father's death Stalin was arrested on 28 April 1953, because he had visited a restaurant with foreign diplomats. He was charged with [[Wiktionary:denigration#Noun|denigration]] of the Soviet Union's leaders, [[Anti-Soviet agitation|anti-Soviet propaganda]] and criminal negligence, and sentenced to eight years in prison.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=225}}</ref>\n\nStalin asked the new Soviet leaders, [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and [[Georgy Malenkov]], for clemency but he was considered a dangerous person, and he was judged in a behind-closed-doors trial and was not allowed legal representation. He was imprisoned in the special penitentiary of [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]] under the name \"Vasily Pavlovich Vasilyev\". He was released from prison on 11 January 1960. The [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] issued him a pension of 300 rubles, an apartment in Moscow, and a three-month treatment vacation in [[Kislovodsk]]. He was also granted permission to wear his general's uniform and all of his military medals.\n\n==Death==\n[[File:\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 (\u043a\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0444) \u0418.\u0412.\u0414\u0436\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0448\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 (\u0421\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430) \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0431\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438.JPG|right|thumb|Stalin's grave in [[Kazan]].]]\nVasily Stalin died on 19 March 1962, due to chronic alcoholism, two days before his 41st birthday.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=230}}</ref> \n\nVasily Stalin was partially [[Rehabilitation (Soviet)|rehabillitated]] in 1999, when the Military Collegium of the Supreme Court lifted charges of anti-Soviet propaganda that dated from 1953. His body was re-buried next to his fourth wife in a Moscow cemetery in 2002.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film ''[[My Best Friend, General Vasili, Son of Joseph Stalin]]'', Vasili Stalin is portrayed by actor Vladimir Steklov.\n*In the 2017 satirical film ''[[The Death of Stalin]]'' he is played by [[Rupert Friend]] and is depicted as being alcoholic and severely unhinged.\n*In the TV series ''\u0421\u044b\u043d \u043e\u0442\u0446\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432'' (The Son of the Father of Nations), Vasily Stalin was played by Gela Meskhi.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{Citation|last=Alliluyeva|first=Svetlana|authorlink=Svetlana Allilueva|translator-last=Johnson|translator-first=Priscilla|title=Twenty Letters to a Friend|year=1967|publisher=Hutchinson|location=London|isbn=0-060-10099-0}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kotkin|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Kotkin|year=2014|title=Stalin, Volume 1: Paradoxes of Power, 1878\u20131928|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York City|ISBN=978-1-59420-379-4}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kotkin|first=Stephen|year=2017|title=Stalin, Volume 2: Waiting for Hitler, 1929\u20131941|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York City|ISBN=978-1-59420-380-0}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kun|first=Mikl\u00f3s|translator-last=Bod\u00f3czky|translator-first=Mikl\u00f3s|translator2-last=Hideg|translator2-first=Rachel|translator3-last=Higed|translator3-first=J\u00e1nos|translator4-last=V\u00f6r\u00f6s|translator4-first=Mikl\u00f3s|year=2003|title=Stalin: An Unknown Portrait|publisher=Central European University Press|location=Budapest|ISBN=963-9241-19-9}}\n* {{Citation|last=Montefiore|first=Simon Sebag|authorlink=Simon Sebag Montefiore|title=Stalin: The Court of the Red Tsar|year=2003|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-0-7538-1766-7}}\n* {{Citation|last=Montefiore|first=Simon Sebag|title=Young Stalin|year=2007|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-0-297-85068-7}}\n* {{Citation|last=Richardson|first=Rosamond|title=The Long Shadow: Inside Stalin's Family|year=1993|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|location=London|isbn=0-316-90553-4}}\n* {{Citation|last=Sullivan|first=Rosemary|authorlink=Rosemary Sullivan|year=2015|title=Stalin's Daughter: The Extraordinary and Tumultuous Life of Svetlana Alliluyeva|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-44341-442-5}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.peoples.ru/military/general/vasiliy_stalin/ Vasiliy Stalin information] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://ava.org.ru/iap/32g.htm Photo of Vasily Stalin in 32 GIAP]\n\n{{Joseph Stalin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stalin, Vasily}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Burials in Troyekurovskoye Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Children of national leaders]]\n[[Category:Inmates of Vladimir Central Prison]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Alexander Nevsky]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Suvorov, 2nd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Grunwald, 3rd class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Red Banner]]\n[[Category:Soviet World War II pilots]]\n[[Category:Soviet Air Force generals]]\n[[Category:Soviet lieutenant generals]]\n[[Category:Soviet rehabilitations]]\n[[Category:Stalin family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{ref improve|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = Vasily Stalin\n| honorific_suffix  = \n| image         = \u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d, 1942 \u0433\u043e\u0434.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Vasily in 1942\n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| birth_name    = Vasily Iosifovich Dzhugashvili \n| other_name    =\n| nickname      = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=y|1921|3|21}}\n| birth_place   = Moscow, [[Russian SFSR]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|df=y|1962|3|19|1921|3|21}}\n| death_place   = [[Kazan]], Russian SFSR, Soviet Union\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Soviet Union|1936}} \n| branch        = [[Soviet Air Forces]]\n| serviceyears  = 1938\u20131953\n| serviceyears_label =\n| rank          = [[File:CCCP army Rank general-lejtnant infobox.svg|30px]] [[Lieutenant general]]\n| rank_label    =\n| servicenumber = \n| unit          = [[1st Baltic Front]]<br>[[1st Belorussian Front]]\n| commands      = \n| battles_label = \n| battles       = [[World War II]] \n*[[Battle of Berlin]]\n| awards        = [[Order of the Red Banner]]\n| spouse        = {{ubl|Galina Burdonskaia|Yekaterina Semyonovna Timoshenko|Kapitolina Georgievna Vasil'yeva|Maria Ignat'yeva Nusberg}}\n| relations     = {{ubl|[[Joseph Stalin]] (father)|[[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]] (mother)|[[Svetlana Alliluyeva]] (sister)|[[Yakov Dzhugashvili]] (half-brother)|[[Konstantin Kuzakov]] (half-brother)}}\n| children      = \n| laterwork     = \n| signature     = \n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n}}\n\n'''Vasily Iosifovich Stalin''' ({{lang-ru|link=no|\u0412\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0301\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0418\u043e\u0301\u0441\u0438\u0444\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0301\u043b\u0438\u043d}}; n\u00e9 '''Dzhugashvili'''; {{lang-ru|link=no|\u0414\u0436\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0448\u0432\u0438\u0301\u043b\u0438}}; 21 March 1921 \u2013 19 March 1962) was the son of [[Joseph Stalin]] by his second wife, [[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]].\n\n==Early life==\nStalin was born on 21 March 1921, the son of [[Joseph Stalin]] and [[Nadezhda Alliluyeva]]. He had an older half-brother, [[Yakov Dzhugashvili]] (born 1907), from his father's first marriage to [[Kato Svanidze]], and a younger sister, [[Svetlana Alliluyeva|Svetlana]], was born in 1926.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=15}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Kotkin|2014|p=466}}</ref> The family also took in [[Artyom Sergeyev]], the son of [[Fyodor Sergeyev]], a close friend of Joseph. Fyodor died four months after the birth of Artyom in an accident, so the boy was raised in the Stalin household.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=351}}</ref>\n\nAs his mother was interested in pursuing a professional career, a [[nanny]], Alexandra Bychokova, was hired to look after Stalin and Svetlana.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|pp=23\u201324}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 1932 his mother shot herself.<ref>{{harvnb|Kotkin|2017|pp=110\u2013111}}</ref> To conceal the suicide, the children were told that Alliluyeva had died of [[peritonitis]], a complication from [[appendicitis]]. It would be 10 years before they learned the truth of their mother's death.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=53}}</ref> Svetlana would later write that the death of their mother had a profound impact on her brother. She noted that he started to [[alcoholism|drink alcohol]] at the age of 13, and in drunken episodes would curse and attack her.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=72}}</ref> \n\nStarting from the death of Alliluyeva, Joseph Stalin ceased to visit his children; only the nursemaid and head of Stalin's security guards looked after Vasily and his sister. One officer, Sergei Efimov, was charged with continuously looking after the two children.\n\n==Military service==\nVasily started his active military service in the 16th Fighter Aviation Regiment in Moscow.{{when|date=January 2019}} Here he met Galina Burdonskaia, his future wife. They married when Vasily was 19.\n\nHe was transferred to the front in August 1941, and given the surname Ivanov in an attempt to conceal his identity. As the son of Stalin he flew in combat rarely, and when he did he was accompanied by a [[Formation flying|formation]]. In total Stalin took part in 29 combat missions, and is said to have shot down two enemy aircraft.<ref name=\"Kun 360>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=360}}</ref> As the son of the Soviet leader, Stalin was hated by most of his colleagues, who felt he was an informant to his father.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=357}}</ref> In the spring of 1942 he was sent back to Moscow, and given a role inspecting the conditions of the air force, and mainly stayed in Moscow for the rest of the war.<ref name=\"Kun 360/> Bored in this role, Stalin found himself in trouble after an 4 April 1943 incident where he had explosives dropped into the [[Moskva River]], injuring himself and killing the flight engineer.<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=361}}</ref> \n\nAs a result of the explosion, Stalin was demoted, though within a year and a half he was promoted to command an air division. He was further promoted to general, and at the age of 24 was made the youngest [[major-general]] in the [[Red Army]]. He was also awarded several decorations, including the [[Order of Red Banner]] (twice), the [[Order of Alexander Nevsky]], and the [[Order of Suvarov]]. After the war he was transferred to Germany as part of the [[Soviet occupation zone|Soviet occupation]].<ref>{{harvnb|Kun|2003|p=362}}</ref>\n\nHe was promoted to major-general in 1946, to Lieutenant-General in 1947, and to Commander of the [[Air Forces of the Moscow Military District]] in 1948.\n\n==Arrest and imprisonment==\nJoseph Stalin died on 4 March 1953. Vasily arrived shortly after the death of his father, and in a drunken rage claimed his father had been poisoned.<ref>{{harvnb|Sullivan|2015|p=184}}</ref> After his father's death, a long period of troubles began for Stalin. The [[Ministry of Defense (Soviet Union)|Defense Ministry]] offered him to take up command of any [[Military districts of the Soviet Union|military district]], but he would only accept Moscow. This was not possible so instead Stalin was forced to retire from the military.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=224}}</ref> Less than two months after his father's death Stalin was arrested on 28 April 1953, because he had visited a restaurant with foreign diplomats. He was charged with [[Wiktionary:denigration#Noun|denigration]] of the Soviet Union's leaders, [[Anti-Soviet agitation|anti-Soviet propaganda]] and criminal negligence, and sentenced to eight years in prison.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=225}}</ref>\n\nStalin asked the new Soviet leaders, [[Nikita Khrushchev]] and [[Georgy Malenkov]], for clemency but he was considered a dangerous person, and he was judged in a behind-closed-doors trial and was not allowed legal representation. He was imprisoned in the special penitentiary of [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]] under the name \"Vasily Pavlovich Vasilyev\". He was released from prison on 11 January 1960. The [[Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] issued him a pension of 300 rubles, an apartment in Moscow, and a three-month treatment vacation in [[Kislovodsk]]. He was also granted permission to wear his general's uniform and all of his military medals.\n\n==Death==\n[[File:\u041c\u043e\u0433\u0438\u043b\u0430 (\u043a\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0444) \u0418.\u0412.\u0414\u0436\u0443\u0433\u0430\u0448\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 (\u0421\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430) \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0431\u0438\u0449\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438.JPG|right|thumb|Stalin's grave in [[Kazan]].]]\nVasily Stalin died on 19 March 1962, due to chronic alcoholism, two days before his 41st birthday.<ref>{{harvnb|Alliluyeva|1967|p=230}}</ref> \n\nVasily Stalin was partially [[Rehabilitation (Soviet)|rehabillitated]] in 1999, when the Military Collegium of the Supreme Court lifted charges of anti-Soviet propaganda that dated from 1953. His body was re-buried next to his fourth wife in a Moscow cemetery in 2002.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film ''[[My Best Friend, General Vasili, Son of Joseph Stalin]]'', Vasili Stalin is portrayed by actor Vladimir Steklov.\n*In the 2017 satirical film ''[[The Death of Stalin]]'' he is played by [[Rupert Friend]] and is depicted as being alcoholic and severely unhinged.\n*In the TV series ''\u0421\u044b\u043d \u043e\u0442\u0446\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432'' (The Son of the Father of Nations), Vasily Stalin was played by Gela Meskhi.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{Citation|last=Alliluyeva|first=Svetlana|authorlink=Svetlana Allilueva|translator-last=Johnson|translator-first=Priscilla|title=Twenty Letters to a Friend|year=1967|publisher=Hutchinson|location=London|isbn=0-060-10099-0}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kotkin|first=Stephen|authorlink=Stephen Kotkin|year=2014|title=Stalin, Volume 1: Paradoxes of Power, 1878\u20131928|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York City|ISBN=978-1-59420-379-4}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kotkin|first=Stephen|year=2017|title=Stalin, Volume 2: Waiting for Hitler, 1929\u20131941|publisher=Penguin Press|location=New York City|ISBN=978-1-59420-380-0}}\n* {{Citation|last=Kun|first=Mikl\u00f3s|translator-last=Bod\u00f3czky|translator-first=Mikl\u00f3s|translator2-last=Hideg|translator2-first=Rachel|translator3-last=Higed|translator3-first=J\u00e1nos|translator4-last=V\u00f6r\u00f6s|translator4-first=Mikl\u00f3s|year=2003|title=Stalin: An Unknown Portrait|publisher=Central European University Press|location=Budapest|ISBN=963-9241-19-9}}\n* {{Citation|last=Montefiore|first=Simon Sebag|authorlink=Simon Sebag Montefiore|title=Stalin: The Court of the Red Tsar|year=2003|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-0-7538-1766-7}}\n* {{Citation|last=Montefiore|first=Simon Sebag|title=Young Stalin|year=2007|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-0-297-85068-7}}\n* {{Citation|last=Richardson|first=Rosamond|title=The Long Shadow: Inside Stalin's Family|year=1993|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|location=London|isbn=0-316-90553-4}}\n* {{Citation|last=Sullivan|first=Rosemary|authorlink=Rosemary Sullivan|year=2015|title=Stalin's Daughter: The Extraordinary and Tumultuous Life of Svetlana Alliluyeva|publisher=HarperCollins|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-44341-442-5}