{"title_page": "Petraio", "text_new": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] quarter of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As the path was trafficked and inhabited, it was improved to a narrow series of connected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio comprises a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Naples_Petraio.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:The Petraio Naples Italy-02.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 03.jpeg|thumb|300px|Pensione Haase, Salita del Petraio]]\n[[File:Petraio Napoli 04.jpeg|thumb|300px]]\nThe '''Petraio''' is a widely-known urban path in [[Naples, Italy]], which descends from what was once an expansive upper agricultural area (the present day hilltop district of [[Vomero]]) and connects with lower neighborhoods before terminating in the [[Chiaia]] quarter of downtown Naples. \n\nFomerly called ''O'Petraro'',<ref name=\"pet5\">{{cite web\n |title        = Ascent of the Petraio\n |publisher    = thesooper.it\n |author       = \n |date         = \n |url          = https://thesooper.it/napoli/luoghi-da-scoprire-a-napoli/aria-aperta/salita-del-petraio/}}</ref> the path was originally a natural, self-formed alluvial channel that followed a narrow watershed, deposting rocks, stones and pebbles, meandering and bifurcating as it descended. As these areas were trafficked and inhabited, the path was improved to a narrow series of interconnected stone walks, alleys, steps and ramps &mdash; varying in slope and width, at points overarched by buildings.<ref name=\"pet8\">{{cite web\n |title        = Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders\n |publisher    = repubblica.it\n |author       = Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata\n |date         = January 14, 2014\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fespresso.repubblica.it%2Fvisioni%2Fcultura%2F2014%2F01%2F14%2Fnews%2Fnapoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref> \n\nProminent sub-sections include:<br/>\n*Gradini (steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Descesa (descending steps) del Petraio<br/>\n*Vico (alley) del Petraio<br/>\n*Largo (widening) del Petraio<br/>\n*Rampe (ramp) del Petraio<br/>\n*Salita (climb) del Petraio<br/> \n\nFramed with residential buildings, churches,and small businesses, the Petraio is accessibly only on foot, and is noted for its broad range of architecture &mdash; from [[Liberty style|Neapolitan Liberty]] villas to its ''bassi,'' small one and two room dwellings directly accessed off the Petraio itself &mdash; as well as its picturesque character and sweeping views of the city.\n\n==Access==\nAt its summit, the Petraio can be accessed via streets in the San Martino section of [[Vomero]], near [[Castel Sant'Elmo]], and at its lower terminus in the area of [[Chiaia]]. The Petraio is served by the ''Palazzolo-Parco Marcolini'' station of the [[Chiaia Funicular]] as well by the ''Petraio'' station of the [[Central Funicular]].  As well, the Petraio can be accessed by numerous cross-streets, including Naples' prominent Corso Vittorio Emanuele.\n<ref name=\"pet2\">{{cite web\n |title        = Access routes to Vomero: the Petraio and S. Francesco\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = February 5, 2015\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/le-vie-daccesso-al-vomero-il-petraio-s-francesco/}}</ref> \n\n*'''The upper Petraio terminus''': {{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=inline|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}} \n\nThe Petraio comprises a subset of Naples more than 200 neighborhood stairs, ramps and pedestrian descents.<ref>{{cite news|author=Donatella Bernab\u00f2 Silorata |date=14 January 2014 |title=Napoli segreta, le scale delle meraviglie |language=it |trans-title=Secret Naples, the stairs of wonders |newspaper=L'Espresso |url=http://espresso.repubblica.it/visioni/cultura/2014/01/14/news/napoli-segreta-le-scale-delle-meraviglie-1.148736}}</ref>\n\n==[[Paul Klee]]==\nOn his 1901-1902<ref name=\"pet6\">{{cite web\n |title        = The Diaries of Paul Klee, 1898-1918\n |publisher    = University of California Press, 1964\n |author       = Felix Klee, editor\n |date         = \n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> soujourn in Italy, noted Swiss-born painter [[Paul Klee]] stayed at Pensione Haase<ref name=\"pet1\">{{cite web\n |title        = IL PETRAIO: TRA STORIA E ABBANDONO\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = \n |date         = May 10, 2017\n |url          = http://www.vomeromagazine.net/il-petraio-tra-storia-e-abbandono/}}</ref> (Salita del Petrajo, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples), a Villa directly adjacent to the Petraio.  In his diaries, he compared Geonoa and Naples:\n\n\"It is already impossible for me to even enumerate what I have seen. Compared to Genoa, Naples is indolent, messy and sick. Compared to Naples, Genoa is one-sided. Naples has the greatest splendor alongside the greatest misery. Port life, carriage ride, high-level opera house, even a piece of Rome: the National Museum. Beside this the heavenly nature, unmatched. The sea of \u200b\u200bGenoa more imposing, but also more monotonous. Here a placid cove, framed by strange mountains and closed by characteristic islands. And all I can see from the balcony of my room. Like a giant amphitheater, the wonderful city with its intense buzz lies at my feet. On the left the old city with the docks of the port and the ancient Vesuvius, on the right the modern Villa Nazionale and Posillipo. All around the house there are gardens of fresh green, fantastic shapes and myriads of flowers. Salita del Petraio, Villa De Rosa 48, Pensione Haase, Naples, is called this fabulous panoramic lookout. The sea is wonderfully blue and calm. The city is a lively picture of clarity, facades of blocks of houses, in the light and darkness, white streets, sections of dark green parks. Faced with such a spectacle one thinks of the temptation of Christ. We are exalted by joy, we are hovering between shining spheres, which have become the center of a world.\"<ref name=\"pet3\">{{cite web\n |title        = Stairs that continue to reveal themselves: the church of the Petraio and the villa where Paul Klee lived\n |publisher    = Vomero Magazine\n |author       = Identitainsorgenti.com\n |date         = October 4, 2017\n |url          = https://translate.google.it/translate?hl=it&sl=it&tl=en&u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.identitainsorgenti.com%2Fnapoli-a-piedi-scale-che-continuano-a-svelarsi-la-chiesa-del-petraio-e-la-villa-dove-dimoro-paul-klee%2F}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n*In the film [[The Four Days of Naples]], in the early stages of the Neapolitan uprising, a young man can be heard shouting: \"Pe 'e criatur' ro Petraio!\".\n*Popularly, the expression salir\u00e8 'ncoppo' is used in Santar\u00e8lla , which indicates the need to go from the Petraio to Villa La Santarella and Piazza Vanvitelli .\n*Author [[Nicola Pugliese]] in his book ''Malacqua'', cites Petraio, describing the origin of his name.\n\n==See Also==\n[[Stairways in Naples]]<br>\n[[Matera]]\n\n{{coord|40|50|35.87|N|14|14|10.70|E|display=title|region:IT_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petraio}}\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Naples]]\n[[Category:Zones of Naples]]\n[[Category:Lists of buildings and structures in Italy|Naples stairways]]\n\n==External References==\n* [https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=it&rurl=translate.google.it&sl=it&sp=nmt4&tl=en&u=http://www.scaledinapoli.com/&usg=ALkJrhjlxbq3eRVLr6oflxJlrzYoms77hA Stairways of Naples]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n", "name_user": "842U", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petraio"}
{"title_page": "Ian Lucas", "text_new": "{{About|the UK politician|the rugby league footballer and coach|Ian Lucas (rugby league)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Update|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Ian Lucas\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Ian C. Lucas crop 2.jpg\n| office2 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Business and Regulatory Reform]]\n| term_start2 = 9 June 2009\n| term_end2 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor2 = New position\n| successor2 = [[Judith Wilcox, Baroness Wilcox|Baroness Wilcox]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| parliament3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[John Marek (politician)|John Marek]]\n| successor3 = [[Sarah Atherton]]\n| term_start3 = 7 June 2001\n| term_end3 = 6 November 2019\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|09|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Gateshead]], [[County Durham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Norah Lucas\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[New College, Oxford]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Ian Colin Lucas''' (born 18 September 1960) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham, Wales]] from [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. He was [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] for Business and Regulatory Reform in the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] from 2009 until Labour's defeat at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]].\n\nHe did not stand at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/assets/pdfs/elections/2019/sopn-nop-wrexham.pdf|title=Statement of Persons Nominated and Notice of Poll - Wrexham Constituency|date=14 November 2019|website=Wrexham County Borough Council|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114233240/https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/assets/pdfs/elections/2019/sopn-nop-wrexham.pdf|archive-date=14 November 2019|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born and brought up in a [[council housing|council house]] in [[Gateshead]], the second son of Colin and Alice Lucas. His father worked as a [[process engineer]] in a local factory, apart from serving in the army from 1942\u20131947 during the [[Second World War]]. He attended Greenwell Junior High School on ''Beacon Lough Road '' in Gateshead then [[Newcastle Royal Grammar School]], and won a place at [[New College, Oxford|New College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]], to study [[jurisprudence]] gaining a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1982. He qualified from the [[University of Law|College of Law]] in 1983 and was admitted as a solicitor in 1985.\n\n==Professional career==\nHe became a [[solicitor]] practising in London from 1983\u20136, but moved to [[Wrexham]] the 1986, specialising in criminal and personal injury law for Percy Hughes and Roberts in [[Chester]] until 1987. He worked for Lees Moore and Price in [[Birkenhead]] until 1989. He then worked for Roberts Moore Nicholas Jones until 1992 in Wrexham.\n\nIn 1992 he moved the short distance to [[Oswestry]] in [[Shropshire]] working for Dr Crawford, and formed his own practice, Crawford Lucas in 1997. The move was precipitated because of disagreements with his old firm when he had organised protests against cuts in legal aid. He was a partner in Stevens Lucas from 2000\u20131. After the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] in 1997, Ian Lucas represented [[Trevor Rees-Jones (bodyguard)|Trevor Rees-Jones]] (Diana's bodyguard, and survivor of the crash) in a legal battle with [[Mohamed Fayed]].\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1986 he joined the Labour Party, and became chairman of the [[Wrexham]] branch. He was on Gresford Community Council in Wrexham from 1987\u201391. He contested the traditionally [[Conservative Party (UK)|conservative]] seat of [[North Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Shropshire]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], but was narrowly defeated. He has served as a [[school governor]], and on a local hospital board.\n\nHe was later selected to stand for the UK Parliament in [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]], and won the seat in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]].\n\nHe was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Bill Rammell]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], [[Minister of State]] for Lifelong Learning, Further and Higher Education. He resigned as PPS on 6 September 2006, due to the refusal by [[Tony Blair]] to name a date for stepping down as Prime Minister. Fellow Welsh Labour MPs [[Wayne David]] and [[Mark Tami]] resigned on the same day.\n\nLucas was promoted by [[Gordon Brown]] in the reshuffle of October 2008, to the role of assistant government whip. He then entered Government as a minister for the first time in the June 2009 reshuffle, becoming [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] for Business and Regulatory Reform in the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]], and held that post until the Labour government left office in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/mps/ian-lucas-mp/ |title=Ian Lucas MP |publisher=Welshlabour.org.uk |date=2012-02-13 |access-date=2012-08-16 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202222641/http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/mps/ian-lucas-mp/ |archive-date=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was the shadow minister for the Middle East and Africa.<ref name=\"huffpost-20140120\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/ian-lucas/central-african-republic-car-crisis_b_4615610.html |title=Crisis in Central African Republic |author=Ian Lucas |publisher=Huffington Post |date=20 January 2014 |accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as a member of the Environmental Audit Select Committee and the Transport Select Committee.\n\nHe has taken an interest in sustainable energy, devolution of powers in [[Wales]], and links with [[Germany]]. He is a member of both the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and the [[Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bnaibrithuk.org/mps-see-israels-predicament-at-board-rep-council-panel/|title=MPs \"see Israel's Predicament\" at Board-Rep Council Panel|publisher=B'nai B'rith UK|date=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nDespite his constituency voting to leave the [[European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]], Lucas supported a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]] on the UK's EU membership.<ref name=\"seat\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-49665710|title=Opposing Brexit could cost me my seat - Labour MP|first=Paul|last=Martin|date=11 September 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He would support remaining in the European Union in the event of such a vote.<ref name=\"seat\"/>\n\nHe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11 March 2019, he alleged that North Wales police, The probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistake made in the management of Jordan James Lee Davidson before the murder of Nicolas Churton. He further alleged that he had been misled about the case by Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police.  The murder case was investigated on two occasions by the Independent Office for Police misconduct, that found procedural failings that contributed to the murder.  The Independent Office for Police misconduct determined it had found no evidence that he had been deliberately misled by the Chief Constable. In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, Arfon Jones, the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\"\n\nLucas did not stand for re-election at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-50021863|title=Wrexham MP Ian Lucas will stand down at next election|date=11 October 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary debate about the murder of Nicolas Churton ==\n\nOn the 11 March 2019, he alleged that North Wales police, The probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistakes made in the management of Jordan James Lee Davidson before the murder of Nicolas Churton. He further alleged that he had been misled about the case by Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police.  The murder case was investigated on two occasions by the Independent Office for Police misconduct, that found procedural failings that contributed to the murder.  The Independent Office for Police misconduct determined it had found no evidence that he had been deliberately misled by the Chief Constable. In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, Arfon Jones, the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ianlucas.co.uk Ian Lucas MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20100412133625/http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/candidates/ian-lucas-wrexham/ Ian Lucas MP] Welsh Labour Party profile\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = ian-lucas/1470 | hansard = mr-ian-lucas | hansardcurr = 1569 | guardian = 6518/ian-lucas | publicwhip = Ian_Lucas | theywork = ian_lucas | record = Ian-Lucas/Wrexham/356 | bbc = 25496.stm | journalisted = }}\n* {{C-SPAN|ianlucas}}\n\n;News articles\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/7542690.stm BBC apologises in August 2008]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7114248.stm Welsh dragon on the Union flag in November 2007]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/6105536.stm Richard Brunstrom in November 2006]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/5320654.stm Leaving government in September 2006]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/5076720.stm Digital TV in June 2006]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/4161143.stm Death by negligent driving in January 2005]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/1962532.stm School merger in May 2002]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/1811178.stm Citizenship in February 2002]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Marek (politician)|John Marek]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]|years=[[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]\u2013[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sarah Atherton]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Labour Party shadow cabinet election, 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lucas, Ian}}\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Gateshead]]\n[[Category:People from Wrexham]]\n[[Category:Politics of Wrexham]]\n[[Category:People educated at the Royal Grammar School, Newcastle upon Tyne]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:British solicitors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of The College of Law]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Israel]]\n[[Category:Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the UK politician|the rugby league footballer and coach|Ian Lucas (rugby league)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2014}}\n{{Update|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Ian Lucas\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Official portrait of Ian C. Lucas crop 2.jpg\n| office2 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Business and Regulatory Reform]]\n| term_start2 = 9 June 2009\n| term_end2 = 11 May 2010\n| predecessor2 = New position\n| successor2 = [[Judith Wilcox, Baroness Wilcox|Baroness Wilcox]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| office3 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]]\n| parliament3 = \n| predecessor3 = [[John Marek (politician)|John Marek]]\n| successor3 = [[Sarah Atherton]]\n| term_start3 = 7 June 2001\n| term_end3 = 6 November 2019\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1960|09|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Gateshead]], [[County Durham]], England\n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = Norah Lucas\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[New College, Oxford]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Ian Colin Lucas''' (born 18 September 1960) is a [[British people|British]] [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] [[politician]], who was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham, Wales]] from [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] to [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]. He was [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] for Business and Regulatory Reform in the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] from 2009 until Labour's defeat at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 General Election]].\n\nHe did not stand at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/assets/pdfs/elections/2019/sopn-nop-wrexham.pdf|title=Statement of Persons Nominated and Notice of Poll - Wrexham Constituency|date=14 November 2019|website=Wrexham County Borough Council|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191114233240/https://www.wrexham.gov.uk/assets/pdfs/elections/2019/sopn-nop-wrexham.pdf|archive-date=14 November 2019|access-date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born and brought up in a [[council housing|council house]] in [[Gateshead]], the second son of Colin and Alice Lucas. His father worked as a [[process engineer]] in a local factory, apart from serving in the army from 1942\u20131947 during the [[Second World War]]. He attended Greenwell Junior High School on ''Beacon Lough Road '' in Gateshead then [[Newcastle Royal Grammar School]], and won a place at [[New College, Oxford|New College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford University]], to study [[jurisprudence]] gaining a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in 1982. He qualified from the [[University of Law|College of Law]] in 1983 and was admitted as a solicitor in 1985.\n\n==Professional career==\nHe became a [[solicitor]] practising in London from 1983\u20136, but moved to [[Wrexham]] the 1986, specialising in criminal and personal injury law for Percy Hughes and Roberts in [[Chester]] until 1987. He worked for Lees Moore and Price in [[Birkenhead]] until 1989. He then worked for Roberts Moore Nicholas Jones until 1992 in Wrexham.\n\nIn 1992 he moved the short distance to [[Oswestry]] in [[Shropshire]] working for Dr Crawford, and formed his own practice, Crawford Lucas in 1997. The move was precipitated because of disagreements with his old firm when he had organised protests against cuts in legal aid. He was a partner in Stevens Lucas from 2000\u20131. After the death of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]] in 1997, Ian Lucas represented [[Trevor Rees-Jones (bodyguard)|Trevor Rees-Jones]] (Diana's bodyguard, and survivor of the crash) in a legal battle with [[Mohamed Fayed]].\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1986 he joined the Labour Party, and became chairman of the [[Wrexham]] branch. He was on Gresford Community Council in Wrexham from 1987\u201391. He contested the traditionally [[Conservative Party (UK)|conservative]] seat of [[North Shropshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Shropshire]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], but was narrowly defeated. He has served as a [[school governor]], and on a local hospital board.\n\nHe was later selected to stand for the UK Parliament in [[Wrexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wrexham]], and won the seat in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]].\n\nHe was [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Bill Rammell]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], [[Minister of State]] for Lifelong Learning, Further and Higher Education. He resigned as PPS on 6 September 2006, due to the refusal by [[Tony Blair]] to name a date for stepping down as Prime Minister. Fellow Welsh Labour MPs [[Wayne David]] and [[Mark Tami]] resigned on the same day.\n\nLucas was promoted by [[Gordon Brown]] in the reshuffle of October 2008, to the role of assistant government whip. He then entered Government as a minister for the first time in the June 2009 reshuffle, becoming [[Parliamentary Under Secretary of State]] for Business and Regulatory Reform in the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]], and held that post until the Labour government left office in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/mps/ian-lucas-mp/ |title=Ian Lucas MP |publisher=Welshlabour.org.uk |date=2012-02-13 |access-date=2012-08-16 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202222641/http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/mps/ian-lucas-mp/ |archive-date=2 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was the shadow minister for the Middle East and Africa.<ref name=\"huffpost-20140120\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/ian-lucas/central-african-republic-car-crisis_b_4615610.html |title=Crisis in Central African Republic |author=Ian Lucas |publisher=Huffington Post |date=20 January 2014 |accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe has served as a member of the Environmental Audit Select Committee and the Transport Select Committee.\n\nHe has taken an interest in sustainable energy, devolution of powers in [[Wales]], and links with [[Germany]]. He is a member of both the [[Labour Friends of Israel]] and the [[Labour Friends of Palestine & the Middle East]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bnaibrithuk.org/mps-see-israels-predicament-at-board-rep-council-panel/|title=MPs \"see Israel's Predicament\" at Board-Rep Council Panel|publisher=B'nai B'rith UK|date=9 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nDespite his constituency voting to leave the [[European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]], Lucas supported a [[Proposed referendum on the Brexit withdrawal agreement|second referendum]] on the UK's EU membership.<ref name=\"seat\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-49665710|title=Opposing Brexit could cost me my seat - Labour MP|first=Paul|last=Martin|date=11 September 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He would support remaining in the European Union in the event of such a vote.<ref name=\"seat\"/>\n\nHe supported [[Owen Smith]] in the failed attempt to replace [[Jeremy Corbyn]] in the [[2016 Labour Party (UK) leadership election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2016/07/which-mps-and-meps-have-nominated-owen-smith/|title=Full list of MPs and MEPs backing challenger Owen Smith|date=2016-07-21|website=LabourList|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11 March 2019, he alleged that North Wales police, The probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistake made in the management of Jordan James Lee Davidson before the murder of Nicolas Churton. He further alleged that he had been misled about the case by Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police.  The murder case was investigated on two occasions by the Independent Office for Police misconduct, that found procedural failings that contributed to the murder.  The Independent Office for Police misconduct determined it had found no evidence that he had been deliberately misled by the Chief Constable. In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, Arfon Jones, the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\"\n\nLucas did not stand for re-election at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-50021863|title=Wrexham MP Ian Lucas will stand down at next election|date=11 October 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Parliamentary debate about the murder of Nicolas Churton ==\n{{Main|Murder of Nicolas Churton#Parliamentary Debate}}\nOn the 11 March 2019, he alleged that North Wales police, The probation service, the community rehabilitation company, the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]], and the [[Independent Office for Police Conduct]] of hiding the mistakes made in the management of Jordan James Lee Davidson before the murder of Nicolas Churton. He further alleged that he had been misled about the case by Mark Polin, the Chief Constable of North Wales Police.  The murder case was investigated on two occasions by the Independent Office for Police misconduct, that found procedural failings that contributed to the murder.  The Independent Office for Police misconduct determined it had found no evidence that he had been deliberately misled by the Chief Constable. In November 2019, Ian Lucas stated that he disagreed with the IPCC findings, and consequently, Arfon Jones, the North Wales [[Police and crime commissioner|Police Crime Commissioner]], said he was \"pursuing a personal vendetta against the former chief constable and impugning his integrity with such distasteful relish\"\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ianlucas.co.uk Ian Lucas MP] ''official constituency website''\n* [https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20100412133625/http://www.welshlabour.org.uk/candidates/ian-lucas-wrexham/ Ian Lucas MP] Welsh Labour Party profile\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = ian-lucas/1470 | hansard = mr-ian-lucas | hansardcurr = 1569 | guardian = 6518/ian-lucas | publicwhip = Ian_Lucas | theywork = ian_lucas | record = Ian-Lucas/Wrexham/356 | bbc = 25496.stm | journalisted = }}\n* {{C-SPAN|ianlucas}}\n\n;News articles\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/north_east/7542690.stm BBC apologises in August 2008]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7114248.stm Welsh dragon on the Union 